
-- Insertion des cinq scénarios
INSERT INTO Scenario (titre, description, objectif, niveau, bruit_recommande, contenu) VALUES

-- 1. LLMNR Poisoning (Beginner)
('LLMNR Poisoning — Capturing a User Hash on the Wire',
 'A first hands-on exercise on the lab: poison LLMNR queries issued by simulated users to capture a NetNTLMv2 hash, and observe how the SIEM reacts.',
 'Use the offensive lab to capture a NetNTLMv2 hash from a domain user by poisoning LLMNR queries on the target network, and observe how (or whether) the SIEM detects the activity.',
 'beginner',
 FALSE,
 '# LLMNR Poisoning — Capturing a User Hash on the Wire\n\n## Objective\n\nUse the offensive lab to capture a NetNTLMv2 hash from a domain user by\npoisoning LLMNR queries on the target network, and observe how (or\nwhether) the SIEM detects the activity.\n\n## Background\n\nTwo simulated users on the lab — `eddard.stark` and `robb.stark` —\nperiodically issue LLMNR queries (visible in the *Lab Vulnerabilities\nInventory*). Any host on the same broadcast segment can respond to\nthose queries and trick the user into authenticating, thus revealing\ntheir NTLMv2 hash.\n\n## What This Scenario Exercises\n\n- MITRE ATT&CK: **T1557.001** (LLMNR/NBT-NS Poisoning and SMB Relay).\n- Detection of suspicious authentication patterns by the Wazuh SIEM.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Open the offensive module** of the platform and select Caldera as\n   the attack engine.\n2. **Choose the target asset.** Pick `winterfell` (`10.2.10.11`) — the\n   simulated users issue queries on the child-domain segment.\n3. **Select the offensive technique.** Search for the technique\n   corresponding to MITRE T1557.001 in the Caldera ability catalog. The\n   technique should describe LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning.\n4. **Run the attack.** Trigger the execution from the platform and let\n   it run for a few minutes, long enough for the simulated users to\n   issue at least one LLMNR query.\n5. **Switch to the defensive module.** Open the Wazuh dashboard and\n   look for alerts produced during the attack window.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- **Platform side.** The Caldera operation completes successfully and\n  reports at least one captured hash in its result panel.\n- **SIEM side.** Wazuh should produce alerts related to unusual\n  authentication activity from a non-domain-controller host. Look for\n  authentication-failure events involving `eddard.stark` or\n  `robb.stark`.\n- **Gap analysis.** Compare what the platform reports as executed and\n  what Wazuh actually detected. If the attack ran but no alert\n  appeared, you have identified a detection gap to investigate in the\n  rule-tuning module.\n\n## Suggested Follow-up\n\nIf the SIEM did not produce any alert, consider this scenario as the\nstarting point for a rule-tuning exercise. Use the *Writing, Testing\nand Deploying a Wazuh Detection Rule* guide to draft a custom rule\nmatching abnormal authentication patterns.'),

-- 2. AS-REP Roasting (Beginner)
('AS-REP Roasting — Extracting a Hash Without Pre-Authentication',
 'Identify a domain account whose Kerberos pre-authentication is disabled, harvest its AS-REP message, and observe the SIEM''s response.',
 'Identify a domain user account whose Kerberos pre-authentication is disabled, request its AS-REP message from the domain controller, and crack it offline to recover the cleartext password. Then verify how the attack appears (or does not appear) in the SIEM.',
 'beginner',
 FALSE,
 '# AS-REP Roasting — Extracting a Hash Without Pre-Authentication\n\n## Objective\n\nIdentify a domain user account whose Kerberos pre-authentication is\ndisabled, request its AS-REP message from the domain controller, and\ncrack it offline to recover the cleartext password. Then verify how the\nattack appears (or does not appear) in the SIEM.\n\n## Background\n\nWhen Kerberos pre-authentication is disabled on an account, any\nunauthenticated user can request an Authentication Service Reply\n(AS-REP) message containing data encrypted with the user''s password\nhash. This message can be cracked offline. The lab includes at least\none account configured in this state (see the *Lab Vulnerabilities\nInventory* for the relevant family).\n\n## What This Scenario Exercises\n\n- MITRE ATT&CK: **T1558.004** (AS-REP Roasting).\n- Detection of unusual Kerberos ticket request patterns.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Open the offensive module** and select Caldera.\n2. **Choose the target asset.** Select `winterfell` (`10.2.10.11`),\n   the domain controller of `north.sevenkingdoms.local`.\n3. **Select the offensive technique.** Look for the technique\n   corresponding to MITRE T1558.004 in the Caldera ability catalog.\n4. **Run the attack.** The execution should enumerate accounts with\n   pre-authentication disabled and request their AS-REP messages.\n5. **Switch to the defensive module.** Open the Wazuh dashboard and\n   filter alerts on the agent `winterfell`.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- **Platform side.** The Caldera operation completes successfully and\n  returns at least one AS-REP hash.\n- **SIEM side.** Wazuh should ideally produce alerts related to\n  Kerberos events on `winterfell`. The relevant Windows event ID is\n  4768 (Kerberos authentication ticket requested), and the events of\n  interest will show the `PreAuthType` field set to `0`.\n- **Gap analysis.** If no alert appeared even though Event ID 4768\n  entries are present in Wazuh, the issue is not collection but\n  detection logic — a rule must be written to flag pre-auth-disabled\n  ticket requests.\n\n## Suggested Follow-up\n\nOnce the hash is captured, consider chaining this scenario with a\nbrute-force cracking exercise (offline, using the captured AS-REP) to\nrecover the cleartext password and pivot to the next stage.'),

-- 3. Kerberoasting (Intermediate, with Noise)
('Kerberoasting — Extracting and Cracking Service Account Hashes',
 'Enumerate domain accounts with SPNs, request service tickets, and learn to distinguish malicious requests from legitimate background activity. Ambient noise is enabled.',
 'Enumerate domain accounts that have a Service Principal Name (SPN) registered, request a Ticket Granting Service (TGS) for each, and extract the encrypted portion for offline cracking. Investigate the SIEM to determine whether the activity stands out from background authentication noise.',
 'intermediate',
 TRUE,
 '# Kerberoasting — Extracting and Cracking Service Account Hashes\n\n## Objective\n\nEnumerate domain accounts that have a Service Principal Name (SPN)\nregistered, request a Ticket Granting Service (TGS) for each, and\nextract the encrypted portion for offline cracking. Investigate the\nSIEM to determine whether the activity stands out from background\nauthentication noise.\n\n## Background\n\nKerberoasting exploits a feature of Kerberos: any authenticated user\ncan request a service ticket for any account that has an SPN. The\nencrypted portion of the ticket is signed with the service account''s\npassword hash, which means it can be cracked offline if the password\nis weak. This scenario activates the platform''s **ambient noise**\nfeature so that the apprentice learns to distinguish the malicious\nticket requests from legitimate ones.\n\n## What This Scenario Exercises\n\n- MITRE ATT&CK: **T1558.003** (Kerberoasting).\n- The ability to filter true positives from false positives in a\n  noisy SIEM.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Enable ambient noise** from the platform configuration before\n   starting the scenario. This will simulate normal user activity on\n   the domain throughout the exercise.\n2. **Open the offensive module** and select Caldera.\n3. **Choose the target asset.** Select any host within the child\n   domain — `winterfell` is a natural choice as it is the domain\n   controller.\n4. **Select the offensive technique.** Look for the technique\n   corresponding to MITRE T1558.003 in the Caldera ability catalog.\n5. **Run the attack.** The execution should enumerate SPNs, request\n   service tickets, and report the captured TGS hashes.\n6. **Switch to the defensive module.** Open the Wazuh dashboard and\n   investigate the alerts produced during the attack window.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- **Platform side.** The Caldera operation completes successfully and\n  returns at least one service ticket hash.\n- **SIEM side.** Wazuh should produce alerts related to service\n  ticket requests (Windows Event ID 4769). With ambient noise active,\n  many such events will originate from legitimate activity. The\n  apprentice''s task is to identify which ticket requests are\n  suspicious — typically those targeting accounts with weak\n  encryption types (RC4) or those issued in rapid succession against\n  many SPNs.\n- **Gap analysis.** Determine whether the SIEM rules currently in\n  place can isolate the malicious requests from the background\n  noise. If they cannot, this is a clear case for rule tuning.\n\n## Suggested Follow-up\n\nThis scenario is a strong candidate for a rule-tuning iteration. The\napprentice should attempt to write a custom Wazuh rule that flags\nTGS requests with suspicious patterns (e.g. RC4 encryption type,\nhigh request frequency from a single source) without flagging the\nlegitimate background traffic.'),

-- 4. ADCS ESC1 (Intermediate)
('ADCS ESC1 — Forging an Administrative Certificate',
 'Exploit a vulnerable certificate template on the AD CS server to obtain an authentication certificate for a Domain Admin, and confront the resulting blind spot in default Wazuh detection.',
 'Exploit a vulnerable certificate template hosted by the Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS) instance on kingslanding to request a certificate that authenticates as a Domain Admin, then observe how the SIEM reports the activity.',
 'intermediate',
 FALSE,
 '# ADCS ESC1 — Forging an Administrative Certificate\n\n## Objective\n\nExploit a vulnerable certificate template hosted by the Active\nDirectory Certificate Services (AD CS) instance on `kingslanding` to\nrequest a certificate that authenticates as a Domain Admin, then\nobserve how the SIEM reports the activity.\n\n## Background\n\nA certificate template on `kingslanding` allows enrollees to specify\nan arbitrary `subjectAltName`. By requesting a certificate for an\naccount that holds Domain Admin privileges (for example\n`sevenkingdoms\\robert.baratheon`), an attacker obtains a valid\nauthentication certificate for that account — without ever knowing\nthe password.\n\n## What This Scenario Exercises\n\n- MITRE ATT&CK: **T1649** (Steal or Forge Authentication\n  Certificates).\n- Detection of certificate-related events, which are easily missed\n  by default rulesets.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Open the offensive module** and select Caldera.\n2. **Choose the target asset.** Select `kingslanding` (`10.2.10.10`),\n   the AD CS server.\n3. **Select the offensive technique.** Look for the technique\n   corresponding to MITRE T1649 in the Caldera ability catalog. It\n   may be referenced as ESC1 in the technique description.\n4. **Run the attack.** The execution should enumerate certificate\n   templates, identify the vulnerable one, and request a certificate\n   that authenticates as a privileged user.\n5. **Switch to the defensive module.** Open the Wazuh dashboard and\n   filter alerts on the agent `kingslanding`.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- **Platform side.** The Caldera operation completes and reports\n  the issuance of a certificate for a target account.\n- **SIEM side.** Wazuh may not produce any alert at all. AD CS\n  events are stored under specific Windows event channels\n  (`Microsoft-Windows-CertificationAuthority`) that are not\n  monitored by default rulesets. The expected raw events are 4886\n  (certificate request received) and 4887 (certificate issued).\n- **Gap analysis.** This scenario is highly likely to expose a real\n  detection gap. If no alert is produced, the apprentice should\n  proceed to rule tuning and craft a custom rule targeting AD CS\n  certificate-issuance events.\n\n## Suggested Follow-up\n\nUse the *Writing, Testing and Deploying a Wazuh Detection Rule*\nguide to draft a rule that alerts whenever a certificate is issued\nwith a non-default `subjectAltName`. This is the most reliable\nindicator of ESC1 abuse.'),

-- 5. Full Attack Chain (Advanced, with Noise)
('Full Attack Chain — From the Network to Domain Compromise',
 'Capstone scenario chaining several techniques into an end-to-end intrusion, executed under ambient noise and concluded by a stage-by-stage gap analysis.',
 'Execute a complete adversary kill chain on the lab, starting from network reconnaissance and ending with full domain compromise via DCSync. Investigate the SIEM under realistic conditions — that is, with ambient noise active throughout the exercise — and identify the detection gaps along the way.',
 'advanced',
 TRUE,
 '# Full Attack Chain — From the Network to Domain Compromise\n\n## Objective\n\nExecute a complete adversary kill chain on the lab, starting from\nnetwork reconnaissance and ending with full domain compromise via\nDCSync. Investigate the SIEM under realistic conditions — that is,\nwith ambient noise active throughout the exercise — and identify the\ndetection gaps along the way.\n\n## Background\n\nThis scenario chains several techniques covered individually in\nearlier scenarios. It is intended as a capstone exercise: the\napprentice has already practiced LLMNR poisoning, hash cracking, and\nbasic Active Directory attacks, and is now required to combine them\ninto an end-to-end intrusion. Ambient noise is mandatory: the\napprentice must extract the malicious activity from a continuous\nstream of legitimate events, as a real SOC analyst would.\n\n## What This Scenario Exercises\n\n- MITRE ATT&CK techniques chained: **T1557.001** (LLMNR Poisoning),\n  **T1110.002** (Password Cracking), **T1087.002** (Account\n  Discovery), **T1021.002** (SMB/Windows Admin Shares Lateral\n  Movement), **T1003.006** (DCSync).\n- The full purple-team cycle: execution, detection, gap analysis\n  and rule tuning, applied to a multi-stage attack.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Enable ambient noise** from the platform configuration.\n2. **Open the offensive module** and select Caldera.\n3. **Stage 1 — Initial access.** Choose `winterfell` as the target\n   asset and run the LLMNR poisoning technique (T1557.001). Capture\n   a NetNTLMv2 hash.\n4. **Stage 2 — Credential cracking.** Use the captured hash to\n   recover a cleartext password offline. The platform may expose\n   this step as a separate Caldera ability or it may be performed\n   externally — follow whichever path the platform supports.\n5. **Stage 3 — Reconnaissance.** With the recovered credentials,\n   run an account discovery technique (T1087.002) on the child\n   domain to map users, groups and privilege relationships.\n6. **Stage 4 — Lateral movement.** Move from the initial foothold\n   to a member host where higher privileges may be obtainable. Use\n   the SMB-based lateral movement technique (T1021.002) to reach\n   `castelblack`.\n7. **Stage 5 — Domain compromise.** Identify an account holding\n   DCSync rights on the parent domain and execute DCSync\n   (T1003.006) against `kingslanding` to replicate the password\n   hashes of all domain accounts.\n8. **Switch to the defensive module.** Open the Wazuh dashboard\n   and reconstruct the attack timeline from the alerts produced.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- **Platform side.** Each Caldera stage completes successfully and\n  the platform''s operation log shows the full chain executed.\n- **SIEM side.** Wazuh should produce alerts at multiple stages,\n  but it is highly unlikely that all stages are detected by the\n  default ruleset, especially against the background of ambient\n  noise. The apprentice''s task is to identify which stages were\n  caught, which were missed, and which generated alerts that were\n  drowned in false positives.\n- **Gap analysis.** Compare the executed chain (offensive view)\n  with the detected chain (defensive view) and produce a stage-by-\n  stage gap analysis. This is the deliverable of the scenario.\n\n## Suggested Follow-up\n\nFor each detection gap identified, perform a full rule-tuning\niteration following the *Writing, Testing and Deploying a Wazuh\nDetection Rule* guide. Then re-run the full chain and verify that\nthe gaps have been closed. This iterative re-test is the hallmark\nof a mature purple-team practice.');